                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>On July 3, British Foreign Secretary <persName corresp="#p_MH1">Herbert
                        Morrison</persName> sent Turkish Foreign Minister <persName corresp="#p_KF1"
                        >Fuad Köprülü</persName> a memorandum proposing a “package deal” in which
                    British support for Turkish membership in <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss>
                    was “contingent upon” Turkey’s willingness to associate itself with the United
                    States, United Kingdom, and France in establishing an integrated allied command
                    headquarters in the Middle East and that subsequently this command be enlarged
                    to include Egypt and the Commonwealth countries, Australia, New Zealand, and
                    South Africa. The Turkish response was affirmative and British officials in
                    Washington subsequently requested United States aid in further “pressuring the
                    Turks along this line” if necessary. See memorandum of conversation, by Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_BJCH1">Bonbright</persName>, July 6, <ref
                        target="frus1951v03p1#pg_554">volume III, part 1, page 554</ref>.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
